              (b), but with a different carrier.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>

          <p>
            For a network that must <em>deliver</em> entanglement so downstream protocols
            can teleport, swap, or distil, heralding is the only viable choice — every
            architecture below relies on it. Postselection remains useful when the
            protocol only needs the classical measurement record at the end. <strong>QKD</strong>
            is the canonical example: BBM92 and Ekert91 entanglement-based QKD use
            coincidence-window postselection plus basis-sifting; MDI-QKD postselects on
            the central node's Bell-state-measurement announcement; even prepare-and-measure
            BB84 sifts (postselects) basis-matched events to build the raw key. None of
            these need a quantum state to survive after measurement, which is why
            postselection works for them.
          </p>
        </Callout>

        <p>
          Different platforms produce entangled pairs in different ways, all of them
          probabilistic and heralded:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Spontaneous parametric down-conversion (SPDC)</strong> in a non-linear
            crystal (PPKTP, BBO, PPLN). A pump photon spontaneously splits into two
            lower-energy photons whose polarisation, time-energy, and momentum are
            correlated by the conservation laws of the conversion. Megahertz pair rates,
            broad bandwidth, room temperature; the workhorse for QKD field deployments and
            Micius-style satellite experiments
            <SourceNote id="kwiat-prl-1995" /><SourceNote id="yin-science-2017" />. The
            chip-integrated variant, <strong>spontaneous four-wave mixing (SFWM)</strong>
            in silicon-photonic waveguides, puts the same physics on a chip.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Atomic-ensemble emission (DLCZ-style)</strong>. A cloud of cold atoms
            emits a Stokes photon entangled with a delocalised collective spin-wave
            excitation in the ensemble. The ensemble doubles as a memory; reading it out
            later releases an idler photon entangled with whatever Bell pair was generated
            <SourceNote id="sangouard-rmp-83" /><SourceNote id="duan-nature-414" />.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Single-emitter matter-photon entanglement</strong>. A trapped ion,
            neutral atom, NV or SiV centre in diamond, or semiconductor quantum dot emits
            a photon entangled with its own internal spin or hyperfine level. The matter
            qubit then holds the entanglement while the photon travels
            <SourceNote id="knaut-nature-2024" />.
          </li>
        </ul>

      </section>

      <section id="uses" data-nav-section>
        <h2>What a Bell pair lets you do</h2>
        <p>
          A single qubit's state cannot be copied. The <strong>no-cloning theorem</strong>
          says there is no unitary <Math tex="U" /> for which
          <Math tex="U(|\\psi\\rangle|0\\rangle) = |\\psi\\rangle|\\psi\\rangle" /> for an
          arbitrary unknown <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />; copying would violate the
          linearity of quantum mechanics <SourceNote id="wootters-nature-1982" />. A signal
          photon cannot be passed through an amplifier and faithfully reproduced either —
          any phase-insensitive amplifier must add at least one quantum of noise per mode,
          which destroys the qubit's state. The consequence is that quantum networks cannot
          reuse the engineering that makes long-distance classical optical fibre work; the
          three primitives below replace it.
        </p>
        <p>
          Each consumes the shared Bell pair (one-shot resource) and uses a classical
          side-channel for the corrections that complete the protocol. The first two —
          teleportation and entanglement swapping — invoke a
          <strong>Bell-state measurement</strong>; the next section unpacks what that
          measurement is and how it is built.
        </p>

        <Grid min="18rem" gap="var(--space-3)">
          <article class="use-card">
            <h3>Teleportation</h3>
            <p>
              Alice has an unknown qubit <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> she wants to transmit
              to Bob. She performs a Bell-state measurement on
              <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> together with her half of the shared Bell pair,
              then sends the 2-bit outcome to Bob over a classical channel. Bob applies the
              corresponding Pauli correction to his half — which is now in state
              <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />. The original at Alice is destroyed in the
              measurement, consistent with no-cloning. Proposed in
              <strong>1993</strong> <SourceNote id="bennett-prl-1993" />.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="use-card">
            <h3>Entanglement swapping</h3>
            <p>
              Alice and a relay station share a Bell pair; the relay and Bob share another.
              The relay performs a Bell-state measurement on its two qubits and sends the
              2-bit result to one of the endpoints, who applies a Pauli correction. Alice
              and Bob now share a Bell pair, even though their qubits never interacted.
              Proposed in <strong>1993</strong>
              <SourceNote id="zukowski-prl-1993" />; the primitive every memory-based
              quantum repeater is built on.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="use-card">
            <h3>Distillation</h3>
            <p>
              Bell pairs delivered through a noisy channel are mixed states with reduced
              fidelity. Distillation protocols consume two (or more) low-fidelity pairs and
              produce one higher-fidelity pair, trading throughput for quality. Together
              with swapping, distillation makes long-distance entanglement distribution
              feasible without per-photon error correction
              <SourceNote id="bennett-pra-1996" />.
            </p>
          </article>
        </Grid>
      </section>

      <section id="bsm" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Bell-state measurement</h2>
        <p>
          A <strong>Bell-state measurement (BSM)</strong> is a joint measurement on two
          qubits in the Bell basis. The outcome is one of four labels —
          <Math tex="|\Phi^+\rangle" />, <Math tex="|\Phi^-\rangle" />,
          <Math tex="|\Psi^+\rangle" />, <Math tex="|\Psi^-\rangle" /> — and the two qubits
          are left in that Bell state. The label is two classical bits; the receiver uses
          those bits to choose which Pauli correction to apply
          (<Math tex="I" />, <Math tex="X" />, <Math tex="Z" />, or <Math tex="XZ" />)
          and recover the intended state.
        </p>
        <p>
          BSM is the operational primitive behind both teleportation (Alice does a BSM on
          her unknown qubit and her half of the shared Bell pair; the 2-bit outcome tells
          Bob which Pauli to apply) and entanglement swapping (a relay does a BSM on one
          half of pair AB and one half of pair BC; the end qubits A and C are left
          entangled, even though they never interacted).
        </p>

        <h3>How a photonic BSM is built</h3>
        <p>
          The canonical linear-optics implementation: the two qubits enter a 50:50 beam
          splitter, the two output ports each go through a polarising beam splitter, and
          four single-photon detectors sit at the four PBS outputs. Two-photon interference
          at the central beam splitter routes the photons in a way that depends on the
          Bell state at the input. The four-detector click pattern is the readout.
        </p>

