          </svg>
          <figcaption>
            The BSM is a <em>measurement</em>: it projects the joint state of two
            indistinguishable photons onto the Bell basis and announces which Bell state
            the projection landed on. Each detector is labelled by port + polarisation:
            <strong>1<sub>H</sub></strong> (port 1, H detector),
            <strong>1<sub>V</sub></strong>, <strong>2<sub>H</sub></strong>,
            <strong>2<sub>V</sub></strong>. The "this shot" panel (top-left) reads
            <strong>clicks → state → bits</strong> for the current outcome; the history
            pane on the right keeps a running log
            <SourceNote id="azuma-rmp-95" /><SourceNote id="lo-prl-mdi-2012" />.
            <br/><br/>
            <strong>The four outcomes.</strong> A full BSM resolves all four Bell-basis
            projections — one 2-bit code per Bell state, mapping directly to the Pauli
            correction Bob applies on his half of the shared pair
            <SourceNote id="nielsen-chuang-qcqi" />:
            <table class="bsm-click-table">
              <thead>
                <tr><th>BS</th><th>PBS</th><th>click pattern</th><th>Bell state</th><th>bits</th><th>Bob's correction</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>bunched</td><td>same detector, same pol</td><td>2× at 1<sub>H</sub> or 2<sub>H</sub></td><td>|Φ⁺⟩</td><td>00</td><td>I</td></tr>
                <tr><td>bunched</td><td>same detector, same pol</td><td>2× at 1<sub>V</sub> or 2<sub>V</sub></td><td>|Φ⁻⟩</td><td>01</td><td>Z</td></tr>
                <tr><td>bunched</td><td>same port, opposite pol</td><td>1<sub>H</sub>+1<sub>V</sub> or 2<sub>H</sub>+2<sub>V</sub></td><td>|Ψ⁺⟩</td><td>10</td><td>X</td></tr>
                <tr><td>antibunched</td><td>different ports, opposite pol</td><td>1<sub>H</sub>+2<sub>V</sub> or 1<sub>V</sub>+2<sub>H</sub></td><td>|Ψ⁻⟩</td><td>11</td><td>XZ</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
            The 2 bits literally are Bob's gate switches — bit 1 toggles X, bit 2 toggles
            Z, so the receiver wires them straight to hardware.
            <br/><br/>
            <strong>The linear-optics catch.</strong> The four states are projected
            identically by an ideal BSM, but linear-optics hardware can only
            <em>distinguish</em> the two Ψ outcomes from each other. The two Φ outcomes
            (|Φ⁺⟩ → 00 and |Φ⁻⟩ → 01) bunch at the same single detector with the same
            polarisation, producing an identical click pattern — Alice cannot tell which
            Φ she got, so neither bit code is deliverable
            <SourceNote id="calsamiglia-aphysb-2001" />. Real linear-optics teleportation
            therefore post-selects on Ψ clicks (the success rows above) and discards
            shots that look like a Φ event. 2 of 4 distinguishable = the 50 % ceiling.
            In the history pane below, Φ rows are shown muted to flag the post-selection.
            <br/><br/>
            <em>Note on inputs.</em> The BSM is fed two photons that are <em>not</em> a
            Bell state — in teleportation, one is the unknown state |ψ⟩ and the other is
            Alice's half of a Bell pair shared with Bob (which has no well-defined
            polarisation state on its own). The two photons must be indistinguishable in
            wavelength, arrival time, and spatial mode, and they must share the same H/V
            polarisation basis. HOM interference at the BS sorts the four Bell-basis
            components by exchange symmetry. The animation samples the projection outcome
            directly each cycle and replays the click pattern that fires for it.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <script type="module" is:inline>
          // BSM animation, top-down layout.
          //
          // Each cycle:
          //   1. Pick a uniformly random input Bell state.
          //   2. Decide the click signature (Lo/Curty/Qi PRL 108.130503):
          //        Ψ⁺: same port, opposite pol → {H1,V1} or {H2,V2}
          //        Ψ⁻: different ports, opposite pol → {H1,V2} or {V1,H2}
          //        Φ±: 2 photons coincident at one of the 4 detectors
          //   3. Animate photons sources → BS → assigned PBSes → assigned
          //      detectors. Polarisation is resolved at the PBS — the
          //      photon glyph switches from a cloud (undefined pol) to
          //      a sharp H or V bar at the PBS.
          //   4. Click flash + bit-cell flash + outcome cells flash
          //      (white-on-black). For Φ outcomes the second outcome
          //      cell stays "—" because only one detector fired.
          //   5. History row prepended; success-rate counter updated.
          const root = document.querySelector("[data-bsm]");
          if (root) {
            const photon = {
              A: root.querySelector('[data-bsm-photon="A"]'),
              B: root.querySelector('[data-bsm-photon="B"]'),
            };
            const glyph = {};
            for (const k of ["A", "B"]) {
              glyph[k] = {
                cloud: photon[k].querySelector('[data-bsm-cloud]'),
                bar:   photon[k].querySelector('[data-bsm-bar]'),
              };
            }
            const detPath = {
              H1: root.querySelector('[data-bsm-result="H1"]'),
              V1: root.querySelector('[data-bsm-result="V1"]'),
              H2: root.querySelector('[data-bsm-result="H2"]'),
              V2: root.querySelector('[data-bsm-result="V2"]'),
            };
            const clicksCell = {
              bg:   root.querySelector('[data-bsm-clicks-bg]'),
              text: root.querySelector('[data-bsm-clicks-text]'),
            };
            const bitsCell = {
              bg:   root.querySelector('[data-bsm-bits-bg]'),
              text: root.querySelector('[data-bsm-bits-text]'),
            };
            const stateLabel = root.querySelector('[data-bsm-state]');
            const rateValue  = root.querySelector('[data-bsm-rate]');
            const ratePct    = root.querySelector('[data-bsm-rate-pct]');
            const HISTORY_ROWS = 12;
            const rows = [];
            for (let i = 0; i < HISTORY_ROWS; i++) {
              const g = root.querySelector(`[data-bsm-row="${i}"]`);
              rows.push({
                group:  g,
                clicks: g.querySelector('.bsm-row-clicks'),
                state:  g.querySelector('.bsm-row-state'),
                bits:   g.querySelector('.bsm-row-bits'),
              });
            }

            // Element coordinates (must match SVG above exactly).
            const SRC_A = { x: 340, y: 80  };
            const SRC_B = { x: 620, y: 80  };
            const BS    = { x: 480, y: 220 };
            const PBS = {
              1: { x: 240, y: 460 },
              2: { x: 720, y: 460 },
            };
            const DET = {
              H1: { x: 100, y: 600 },
              V1: { x: 380, y: 600 },
              V2: { x: 580, y: 600 },
              H2: { x: 860, y: 600 },
            };
            const DET_KEYS = ["H1", "V1", "H2", "V2"];
            const polOf = (k) => k[0];                  // "H" or "V"
            const portOf = (k) => +k[1];                // 1 or 2
            const pbsOf = (k) => PBS[portOf(k)];
            const SUB = { H: "ₕ", V: "ᵥ" };
            const shortKey = (k) => k[1] + SUB[k[0]];   // "H1" → "1ₕ" (Unicode subscript)

            // Nielsen & Chuang bit convention. Linear-optics BSM only
            // identifies the two Ψ states; Φ outcomes get discarded.
            const STATE_BITS    = { "Φ+": "00", "Φ-": "01", "Ψ+": "10", "Ψ-": "11" };
            const STATE_DISPLAY = { "Φ+": "Φ⁺", "Φ-": "Φ⁻", "Ψ+": "Ψ⁺", "Ψ-": "Ψ⁻" };
            const isSuccess = (state) => state[0] === "Ψ";
            const clicksFor = (o) => shortKey(o.a) + " + " + shortKey(o.b);
            const bitsFor   = (o) => STATE_BITS[o.state];
            const ketFor    = (state) => "|" + STATE_DISPLAY[state] + "⟩";

            function setPos(g, x, y) { g.setAttribute("transform", `translate(${x} ${y})`); }
            function show(g)         { g.setAttribute("opacity", "1"); }
            function hide(g)         { g.setAttribute("opacity", "0"); }
            function setCloud(tag) {
              glyph[tag].cloud.setAttribute("opacity", "1");
              glyph[tag].bar.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
            }
            function setBar(tag, pol) {
              glyph[tag].cloud.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
              glyph[tag].bar.setAttribute("opacity", "1");
              glyph[tag].bar.setAttribute("transform", `rotate(${pol === "H" ? 0 : 90})`);
            }
            function setDetAll(op) {
              for (const k of DET_KEYS) detPath[k].setAttribute("opacity", String(op));
            }
            function lockDet(keys) {
              for (const k of DET_KEYS) {
                detPath[k].setAttribute("opacity", keys.includes(k) ? "1" : "0.08");
              }
            }
            function setFlowCell(cell, value, active) {
              cell.text.textContent = value;
              cell.text.classList.toggle("bsm-flow-text--active", active);
              cell.bg.setAttribute("opacity", active ? "1" : "0");
            }
            function setStateLabel(state, active) {
              stateLabel.textContent = state === null ? "—" : ketFor(state);
              stateLabel.classList.toggle("bsm-flow-state--success", active && isSuccess(state));
              stateLabel.classList.toggle("bsm-flow-state--fail",    active && !isSuccess(state));
            }

            function pickOutcome() {
              const state = ["Ψ+", "Ψ-", "Φ+", "Φ-"][Math.floor(Math.random() * 4)];
              const coin = Math.random() < 0.5;
              if (state === "Ψ+") {
                return coin ? { state, a: "H1", b: "V1" } : { state, a: "H2", b: "V2" };
              }
              if (state === "Ψ-") {
                return coin ? { state, a: "H1", b: "V2" } : { state, a: "V1", b: "H2" };
              }
              const det = DET_KEYS[Math.floor(Math.random() * 4)];
              return { state, a: det, b: det };
            }

            const log = [];
            let identified = 0;
            let total      = 0;
            function pushHistory(o) {
              total += 1;
              const success = isSuccess(o.state);
              if (success) identified += 1;
              log.unshift({
                clicks: clicksFor(o),
                state:  ketFor(o.state),
                bits:   bitsFor(o),
                success,
              });
              if (log.length > HISTORY_ROWS) log.length = HISTORY_ROWS;
              for (let i = 0; i < HISTORY_ROWS; i++) {
                const r = rows[i];
                const e = log[i];
                if (!e) {
                  r.group.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
                  continue;
                }
                r.group.setAttribute("opacity", "1");
                r.clicks.textContent = e.clicks;
                r.state.textContent  = e.state;
                r.bits.textContent   = e.bits;
                for (const cell of [r.clicks, r.state, r.bits]) {
                  cell.classList.toggle("bsm-row--success",  e.success);
                  cell.classList.toggle("bsm-row--fail",    !e.success);
                  cell.classList.toggle("bsm-row--latest", i === 0);
                }
              }
              rateValue.textContent = identified + " / " + total;
              const pct = total === 0 ? 0 : Math.round(100 * identified / total);
              ratePct.textContent = pct + "%";
            }

            const reduced = matchMedia("(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)").matches;

            if (reduced) {
              const sampleShot = { state: "Ψ+", a: "H1", b: "V1" };
              setPos(photon.A, DET.H1.x, DET.H1.y);
              setPos(photon.B, DET.V1.x, DET.V1.y);
              setBar("A", "H");
              setBar("B", "V");
              show(photon.A); show(photon.B);
              lockDet(["H1", "V1"]);
              setFlowCell(clicksCell, clicksFor(sampleShot), true);
              setFlowCell(bitsCell,   bitsFor(sampleShot),   true);
              setStateLabel(sampleShot.state, true);
              const sample = [
                { state: "Ψ+", a: "H1", b: "V1" },
                { state: "Φ-", a: "V1", b: "V1" },
                { state: "Ψ-", a: "H1", b: "V2" },
                { state: "Φ+", a: "H2", b: "H2" },
                { state: "Ψ+", a: "H2", b: "V2" },
                { state: "Φ+", a: "V2", b: "V2" },
                { state: "Ψ-", a: "V1", b: "H2" },
                { state: "Φ-", a: "H1", b: "H1" },
              ];
              for (const e of sample.slice().reverse()) pushHistory(e);
            } else {
              const T_IN    = 1100;
              const T_PAUSE =  350;
              const T_OUT1  =  550;
              const T_OUT2  =  650;
              const T_CLICK =  200;
              const T_HOLD  = 1500;
              const T_RESET =  400;
              const CYCLE   = T_IN + T_PAUSE + T_OUT1 + T_OUT2 + T_CLICK + T_HOLD + T_RESET;
              const P_IN_END    = T_IN;
              const P_PAUSE_END = P_IN_END    + T_PAUSE;
              const P_OUT1_END  = P_PAUSE_END + T_OUT1;
              const P_OUT2_END  = P_OUT1_END  + T_OUT2;
              const P_CLICK_END = P_OUT2_END  + T_CLICK;
              const P_HOLD_END  = P_CLICK_END + T_HOLD;

              const ease = (t) => t < 0.5 ? 2*t*t : 1 - Math.pow(-2*t + 2, 2) / 2;

              const PULSE_DUR = 320;
              const pulseEnd = { H1: 0, V1: 0, H2: 0, V2: 0 };
              let pulseActive = false;

              // Continuous animation, EPR-demo pattern. `cycleStart` is
              // bumped at the end of each cycle (no modulo on elapsed),
              // and we deliberately don't gate on an IntersectionObserver
              // — the rAF clock keeps ticking, and the browser already
              // throttles offscreen rAF for free. This is what stops the
              // "reset when you scroll" feeling that the modulo approach
              // had: with modulo, a long off-screen pause leaves the
              // per-cycle flags stale; with cycleStart-reset-on-completion
              // every cycle is a clean state.
              let cycleStart = 0;
              let outcome = pickOutcome();
              let recorded = false;
              let barsSet = false;
              let pausePosSet = false;
              let resetDone = false;

              function frame(now) {
                const elapsed = now - cycleStart;

                if (elapsed < P_IN_END) {
                  const t = ease(elapsed / T_IN);
                  setPos(photon.A, SRC_A.x + (BS.x - SRC_A.x) * t,
                                   SRC_A.y + (BS.y - SRC_A.y) * t);
                  setPos(photon.B, SRC_B.x + (BS.x - SRC_B.x) * t,
                                   SRC_B.y + (BS.y - SRC_B.y) * t);
                } else if (elapsed < P_PAUSE_END) {
                  if (!pausePosSet) {
                    setPos(photon.A, BS.x - 6, BS.y + 4);
                    setPos(photon.B, BS.x + 6, BS.y + 4);
                    pausePosSet = true;
                  }
                } else if (elapsed < P_OUT1_END) {
                  const t = ease((elapsed - P_PAUSE_END) / T_OUT1);
                  const pbsA = pbsOf(outcome.a);
                  const pbsB = pbsOf(outcome.b);
                  const sameDet = outcome.a === outcome.b;
                  const dxA = sameDet ? -6 : 0;
                  const dxB = sameDet ?  6 : 0;
                  setPos(photon.A,
                    BS.x + (pbsA.x - BS.x) * t + dxA * t,
                    BS.y + (pbsA.y - BS.y) * t);
                  setPos(photon.B,
                    BS.x + (pbsB.x - BS.x) * t + dxB * t,
                    BS.y + (pbsB.y - BS.y) * t);
                } else if (elapsed < P_OUT2_END) {
                  if (!barsSet) {
                    setBar("A", polOf(outcome.a));
                    setBar("B", polOf(outcome.b));
                    barsSet = true;
                  }
                  const t = ease((elapsed - P_OUT1_END) / T_OUT2);
                  const pbsA = pbsOf(outcome.a);
                  const pbsB = pbsOf(outcome.b);
                  const detA = DET[outcome.a];
                  const detB = DET[outcome.b];
                  const sameDet = outcome.a === outcome.b;
                  const dxA = sameDet ? -6 * (1 - t) : 0;
                  const dxB = sameDet ?  6 * (1 - t) : 0;
                  setPos(photon.A,
                    pbsA.x + (detA.x - pbsA.x) * t + dxA,
                    pbsA.y + (detA.y - pbsA.y) * t);
                  setPos(photon.B,
                    pbsB.x + (detB.x - pbsB.x) * t + dxB,
                    pbsB.y + (detB.y - pbsB.y) * t);
                } else if (elapsed < P_HOLD_END) {
                  if (!recorded) {
                    const keys = outcome.a === outcome.b
                      ? [outcome.a]
                      : [outcome.a, outcome.b];
                    const success = isSuccess(outcome.state);
                    hide(photon.A); hide(photon.B);
                    lockDet(keys);
                    setFlowCell(clicksCell, clicksFor(outcome), true);
                    // Φ rows show the projected bits but muted — those
                    // outcomes are post-selected out in real LO BSM.
                    setFlowCell(bitsCell, bitsFor(outcome), success);
                    setStateLabel(outcome.state, true);
                    for (const k of keys) pulseEnd[k] = now + PULSE_DUR;
                    pulseActive = true;
                    pushHistory(outcome);
                    recorded = true;
                  }
                } else if (elapsed < CYCLE) {
                  if (!resetDone) {
                    hide(photon.A); hide(photon.B);
                    setDetAll(0.2);
                    setFlowCell(clicksCell, "—", false);
                    setFlowCell(bitsCell,   "—", false);
                    setStateLabel(null, false);
                    resetDone = true;
                  }
                } else {
                  // Cycle complete — start a fresh cycle. After a long
                  // offscreen pause, this branch fires once on the first
                  // visible frame and the next cycle plays cleanly from
                  // the start.
                  cycleStart = now;
                  outcome = pickOutcome();
                  recorded = false;
                  barsSet = false;
                  pausePosSet = false;
                  resetDone = false;
                  setDetAll(0.2);
                  setCloud("A"); setCloud("B");
                  show(photon.A); show(photon.B);
                  setFlowCell(clicksCell, "—", false);
                  setFlowCell(bitsCell,   "—", false);
                  setStateLabel(null, false);
                }

                if (pulseActive) {
                  let anyActive = false;
                  for (const k of DET_KEYS) {
                    const remaining = pulseEnd[k] - now;
                    if (remaining > 0) {
                      detPath[k].setAttribute(
                        "stroke-width", String(1.5 + 3 * (remaining / PULSE_DUR)));
                      anyActive = true;
                    } else if (pulseEnd[k] !== 0) {
                      detPath[k].setAttribute("stroke-width", "1.5");
                      pulseEnd[k] = 0;
                    }
                  }
                  pulseActive = anyActive;
                }
                requestAnimationFrame(frame);
              }

              // Prime the very first cycle: cloud glyphs visible at the
              // sources, blank readouts. Then start the rAF loop.
              setCloud("A"); setCloud("B");
              show(photon.A); show(photon.B);
              setPos(photon.A, SRC_A.x, SRC_A.y);
              setPos(photon.B, SRC_B.x, SRC_B.y);
              cycleStart = performance.now();
              requestAnimationFrame(frame);
            }
          }
        </script>

        <h3>Why only half the time, on photons</h3>
        <p>
          The 50% ceiling is fundamental to linear-optics BSM, not a hardware limitation:
          no arrangement of beam splitters, phase shifters, and detectors that uses only
          the two input photons can do better. Calsamiglia and Lütkenhaus proved this as
          an upper bound for dual-rail / polarisation encodings without ancillas
          <SourceNote id="calsamiglia-aphysb-2001" />; Azuma's review re-derives it next
          to the click-pattern table for the same apparatus this animation uses
          <SourceNote id="azuma-rmp-95" />. Lifting the bound requires either ancilla
          photons in the apparatus or genuine non-linearity (cross-Kerr media, Rydberg
          interactions, atom–photon gates). A demonstration exceeding 50 % with
          squeezed-light ancillas exists <SourceNote id="bayerbach-sciadv-2023" />, but
          at a hardware cost that has not yet entered fielded systems.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Matter-qubit BSMs</strong> — performed on two stationary qubits sitting
          in the same node (two trapped-ion register slots, two NV-centre spins, two
          superconducting qubits on the same chip) — are <em>deterministic in principle</em>.
          The textbook recipe is CNOT followed by a Hadamard on the control followed by a
          single-qubit computational-basis readout of each qubit; the four 2-bit outcomes
          label the four Bell states one-to-one
          <SourceNote id="nielsen-chuang-qcqi" />. Success probability reduces to the
          fidelity of the underlying CNOT and readout — today routinely 99 %+ on
          trapped-ion, neutral-atom, and superconducting hardware — so "close to 100 %"
          is shorthand for "as good as the gate stack on that platform". Two-qubit gate
          and readout times are platform-specific (≈10–100&nbsp;μs gates and ≈100&nbsp;μs–1&nbsp;ms
          readout on trapped ions, ≈1&nbsp;μs gates on NV, ≈50–300&nbsp;ns gates on
          superconducting circuits) <SourceNote id="meddeb-comnet-2025" />, so a matter
          BSM is several orders of magnitude slower than a photonic linear-optics BSM
          (nanoseconds — set by optical path length plus detector response).
        </p>
        <p>
          Where each kind of BSM sits in a real network: the BSM <em>between two distant
          nodes</em> (for entanglement swapping at a repeater, or for the central node in
          MDI-QKD <SourceNote id="lo-prl-mdi-2012" />) is performed on photons at a
          midpoint Bell-state-analyser station, with the photonic 50 % retry overhead
          baked into the architecture. Matter BSM is used <em>inside</em> a single node —
          for example, to teleport a qubit between two memory slots in the same register,
          or to project onto the Bell basis as part of an intra-node operation in a
          processing repeater.
        </p>
      </section>


      <section id="requirements" data-nav-section>
        <h2>What it takes to deliver Bell pairs</h2>
        <p>
          The link-layer service of a quantum network is <q>deliver Bell pair (A, B)</q>
          on demand <SourceNote id="kozlowski-rfc9340" />. Once delivered, the application
          layer can teleport, distil, swap, or measure as it likes. The network does not
          transport classical messages or copy arbitrary qubits — it distributes
          entanglement between named endpoints, and everything else is built on top.
        </p>
        <p>
          Providing that service end-to-end requires every piece below working at adequate
          rate, fidelity, and reach. Each is a separate engineering challenge, covered in
          a dedicated subject later in the series.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Sources</strong> — generate the entangled pairs in the first place
            (SPDC, atomic-ensemble, single-emitter). <em>Covered above.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Distribution</strong> — place one half of a generated pair at each of
            two distant nodes across a single link, via one of the MM / SR / MS
            architectures. <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>distribution</strong>
            <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Memory</strong> — hold a qubit while its partner photon is in flight,
            with coherence longer than the link's classical round-trip.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>memories</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Reach extension</strong> — chain Bell-state measurements across
            multiple hops so entanglement spans further than a single link can reach.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>swapping</strong> <em>and</em>
            <strong>repeaters</strong> <em>subjects.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Fidelity extension</strong> — distillation trades two noisy pairs for
            one cleaner pair, so the delivered fidelity is high enough for downstream use.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>distillation</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Physical channel</strong> — fibre, hollow-core fibre, free-space, or
            satellite. Loss bounds reach; the channel choice sets the loss budget.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>links</strong> <em>and</em>
            <strong>metrics</strong> <em>subjects.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Protocol stack</strong> — link-layer scheduling, routing, addressing,
            and the classical side-channel needed by every protocol on this page.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>protocols</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </Stack>
  </Center>
</Infographic>

